## What happened

`DSA` has been on a deprecation path since **.NET 7**, when it was marked `[Obsolete]` with diagnostic **`SYSLIB0030`**. On macOS, .NET uses Apple's **Security.framework** as its native crypto provider, and Apple dropped DSA support from that framework. In .NET 10, a managed fallback still kept `DSA.Create()` working, but in .NET 11 that fallback was removed â€” so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

Windows (CNG) and Linux (OpenSSL) still have native DSA support, which is why those platforms continue to work.

## How to fix it

You have two practical options:

### Option 1 â€” Use BouncyCastle (recommended for "verify-only" legacy signatures)

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

// Import your existing DSA public key (e.g. from an X.509 SubjectPublicKeyInfo blob)
DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey =
    (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(spkiBytes);

ISigner verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA"); // or SHA256withDSA
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);

bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signatureBytes);
```

This is pure managed code â€” no platform-native dependency â€” so it works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS.

### Option 2 â€” Migrate to a modern algorithm

If you control both the signing and verifying sides, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, which are supported on all platforms in .NET 11:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
byte[] sig  = ecdsa.SignData(message, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
bool valid  = ecdsa.VerifyData(message, sig, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Summary

| Path | When to use |
|---|---|
| **BouncyCastle** | You must verify existing DSA signatures you can't re-sign |
| **ECDSA / Ed25519** | You control both sides and can rotate keys |

Since you described the use-case as "verify **legacy** DSA signatures," BouncyCastle is the right short-term fix. Long-term, plan to retire the DSA keys entirely.
